We also used the print function and gave it an input or rather an argument.

3
00:00:15,400 --> 00:00:19,760
So in this lesson, I wanted to quickly cover Dart functions.

4
00:00:19,760 --> 00:00:26,200
So if you already know what an argument is, what return does, and what a function does,

5
00:00:26,200 --> 00:00:30,480
then feel free to skip this lesson and head over to the next one where we continue building

6
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:32,400
out our flutter app.

7
00:00:32,400 --> 00:00:36,240
But for those of you guys who are staying with me, functions, as you can guess from

8
00:00:36,240 --> 00:00:43,600
the name, are there to give your app or you give your program some functionality, right?

9
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:48,760
Now in this lesson, I want to talk about functions in the most fundamental sense, and when we're

10
00:00:48,760 --> 00:00:55,360
using functions as programmers, fundamentally, we're trying to package bits of code together

11
00:00:55,360 --> 00:01:02,760
into a block, and to call that block of code repeatedly, saving ourselves from typing

12
00:01:02,760 --> 00:01:05,960
the same code again and again and again.

13
00:01:05,960 --> 00:01:14,680
So for example, if you had a little housekeeping robot this guy, his name is beatbop, and he

14
00:01:14,680 --> 00:01:16,360
does a number of things, right?

15
00:01:16,360 --> 00:01:20,080
For example, he'll go and get you milk every day.

16
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:24,800
But you have to tell him how to do it, you have to tell him to leave the house, move right

17
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:31,600
two blocks, move up four blocks, then move right two blocks, get the milk, come back,

18
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:37,560
and you have to specify all these instructions to him because he's a robot and he doesn't

19
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:43,760
understand contextual information like go to the store and get me some milk.

20
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:49,640
Now if you had to do this day after day after day, every single time you wanted milk, your

21
00:01:49,640 --> 00:01:55,600
fingers would start hurting and you wouldn't want to keep typing out the same instructions,

22
00:01:55,600 --> 00:01:56,600
right?

23
00:01:56,600 --> 00:01:58,200
So what can you do?

24
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:01,800
Well, we're programmers, we're born to be lazy.

25
00:02:01,800 --> 00:02:09,580
So what we can do instead is we can take all these instructions that the robot understands,

26
00:02:09,580 --> 00:02:13,920
and we can package it into a block of code.

27
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:21,200
Now a block of code in many, many programming languages is represented by code that inside

28
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:24,160
a set of curly braces.

29
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:31,460
Once we've got all our instructions inside our curly braces, we can give that block of code

30
00:02:31,460 --> 00:02:35,880
a name, and in this case we've called it get milk.

31
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:43,040
Now every time I need some milk, I can tell the robot get milk and he'll know what to do

32
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:48,080
because we'll find this function called get milk and look inside it to see what it should

33
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:49,080
do.

34
00:02:49,080 --> 00:02:52,200
It's almost like I'm creating a recipe, right?

35
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:57,040
It's like I want to eat cookies, but I don't want to bake cookies.

36
00:02:57,040 --> 00:03:03,080
So let me write down a recipe and give it to my housekeeping robot so that they can make

37
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:04,640
it for me.

38
00:03:04,640 --> 00:03:11,200
And that recipe or the name of the recipe is basically the name of our function.

39
00:03:11,200 --> 00:03:17,000
And not the way that you would create the function looks like this.

40
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:22,480
We've got the name of the function, which is called get milk, and then we've got the curly

41
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:29,520
braces which enclose all of the things that should happen when this function gets called.

42
00:03:29,520 --> 00:03:35,360
And then later on we actually need to use it, we will call the function or tell the computer

43
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:43,000
to execute all of this by writing something like this, giving the name of the function.

44
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:49,040
Now this is called a name to function, well it makes sense because it's got a name, right?

45
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:52,440
We can identify it by what it's called.

46
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:59,000
Now if we dropped everything other than just the core parts, namely the parentheses and the

47
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:04,640
curly braces and all the instructions, then this would become an anonymous function because

48
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:07,600
it doesn't have a name, right?

49
00:04:07,600 --> 00:04:11,360
And these anonymous functions are legion.

50
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:15,880
No just kidding, these anonymous functions are actually very useful.

51
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:22,400
They allow us to tell the computer to do something without explicitly having to create this entire

52
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:26,400
function and give it a name and call its name.

53
00:04:26,400 --> 00:04:33,560
When we were coding up our on-pressed, which expected a void core back, it essentially wanted

54
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:40,840
an anonymous function, we passed in the two empty parentheses and we gave it the block

55
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:45,960
of code that we want to be executed when the button got pressed.

56
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:51,280
This is all you need to know about functions so far to be able to understand what's happening

57
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:53,000
in our flat button.

58
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:57,880
A little bit later on when we level up and we talk about functions in more detail, we'll

59
00:04:57,960 --> 00:05:03,920
talk more about what goes in these parentheses, namely some inputs into the function and

60
00:05:03,920 --> 00:05:10,160
also we'll talk about the return statement when we want our function to output something.

61
00:05:10,160 --> 00:05:14,120
But for now, just know that this is an anonymous function.

62
00:05:14,120 --> 00:05:17,560
It has a set of parentheses and a set of curly braces.

63
00:05:17,560 --> 00:05:22,640
In the curly braces, we say what should happen.

64
00:05:22,640 --> 00:05:26,840
So now that we're all caught up, in the next lesson, we're going to get back to coding

65
00:05:26,880 --> 00:05:33,120
up our dice app and we're going to get our button to change our dice images to actually

66
00:05:33,120 --> 00:05:34,120
make the app work.

